Creamy Avocado Pasta Salad ü•ëüçùüçÖüòã
Via @natashaskitchen
~
The secret ingredient in this Creamy Avocado Pasta Salad recipe will shock you! This avocado pasta salad is easy, creamy, vibrant, fresh and so satisfying!
~
4 cups lightly packed (about 3 oz) fresh baby spinach
4 Tbsp lemon juice (from 1 large lemon)
1 garlic clove, sliced
3 medium avocados (2 for the dressing, 1 for salad)
12 oz rotini pasta
1 cup (half of a 10 oz bag) frozen sweet peas
1 cup (half of a 10 oz bag) frozen corn
2 cups (1 pint) Baby tomatoes, halved
1 tsp sea salt and 1/4 tsp black pepper, or to taste

How To Make Creamy Avocado Pasta Salad:
Cook pasta according to package instructions ‚Äì I cooked 12 oz pasta in 4 Qts water with 1 Tbsp salt and boiled 10 minutes. About 4 minutes before your pasta is done cooking, add frozen peas and frozen corn and cook 4 minutes or until veggies are crisp tender. Rinse under running cold water to chill the pasta. Drain well and transfer to a large mixing bowl. In a food processor or blender, combine half of the spinach, 2 quartered avocados, 4 Tbsp lemon juice, 1 sliced garlic clove, 1 tsp salt and 1/4 tsp black pepper. Pulse until blended then add remaining spinach and blend until creamy and smooth.
Add avocado dressing to pasta bowl along with sliced tomatoes and 1 remaining sliced avocado. Toss salad together until evenly coated. Season to taste with more salt and black pepper.
~

Happy Friday! I made this Spinach, Tomato & Feta two egg omelette with fresh dill for brunch today along with half an avocado and lemony arugula salad with toasted pumpkin seeds! It was absolutely delicious and it totally hit the spot. By the way this combo could be made in advance and re-heats very well on the go if you don‚Äôt have time to whip it up in the AM (just like egg muffins). To make the omelette beat two eggs with a splash of milk in a bowl. Melt a little butter in a GOOD oven safe non-stick pan on the stove top. Add chopped tomatoes and let cook for 30 seconds. Add a handful of spinach and stir the veggies in the pan until the spinach wilts. Spread veggies evenly around the pan. Make sure heat is set to medium then add the eggs over the veggies, crumble feta on top and sprinkle with fresh chopped dill. Let the eggs sit for 2-3 minutes until eggs are mostly set then transfer to an oven set to broil and finish cooking the top about 2-3 minutes. Makes a fail proof omelette every single time! I hope you‚Äôre having a great day.

I shared this fruit tree with my friends the other day and it was a total hit! üòã It‚Äôs very easy to grab the fruit off the toothpicks and of course aesthetically pleasing.‚†Ä

What you need:‚†Ä

What to do:‚†Ä
Step 1 - Slice off the edges of the pineapple & the top. Cut an extra top slice for the star (make sure it‚Äôs thick enough so the star isn‚Äôt flimsy).‚†Ä

It‚Äôs the season of ‚Äúhealthy swaps‚Äù in delicious holiday meals and desserts - here‚Äôs my take on it: ‚Äúhealthy swaps‚Äù aren‚Äôt always healthy emotionally and mentally. üò¨ And I‚Äôm so tired of seeing this BS on Instagram - ESPECIALLY in holiday foods. Please note that if you have allergies - this post isn‚Äôt about swapping ingredients to accommodate. It‚Äôs about how, for whatever reason, on IG everything we eat just has to have some nutritional benefit (not true).
.
üòê Zucchini noodles are a vegetable, not pasta. Processed cauliflower isn‚Äôt the same as actual rice. Rice cake pizza is so far from regular pizza I don‚Äôt even want to call it that- it‚Äôs more of a rice cake cheese melt you know?
.
ü§îI think these swaps make sense sometimes, of course- when the swap you‚Äôre making HONORS your craving. (Like if you‚Äôre actually craving a rice cake pizza or cauliflower rice, obviously that‚Äôs a great choice)
.
ü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èBut I‚Äôm tired of diet culture feeding us the idea that these ‚Äúhealthy swaps‚Äù taste as good as the ‚Äúreal‚Äù thing. It‚Äôs just not true! (unless you just dislike the taste and experience of legit pizza or real pasta, I mean.. fine)
.
ü§¨The way diet culture demonizes carbs in general really bugs me. We literally need carbs (rice, pasta, bread etc) to survive. Just look at the history of food all over the world: carbs have been an essential source of energy for centuries... and now we have decided they‚Äôre bad? No thanks. I‚Äôll take my carbs because I want my brain to function properly.
.
‚ùìSomething to think about: are you honoring your cravings? Are you making food choices based on what you really want or what you think is going to give you the body you want? And do your choices really satisfy you?
.
üôèüèºWhy I care: I can‚Äôt stand the thought of people in my community depriving themselves of real pizza and going for this rice cake pizza BS if that‚Äôs not what they actually want. Give yourself permission to eat the pizza. You don‚Äôt have to EARN it. You don‚Äôt have to justify it with exercise. The best (and really only) way to manage cravings is by eating the thing you crave with full permission and no judgement.
